Bid Alert No.:  12027273
Agency Bid No.:  36C24220Q0263
Title:  Environmental Consulting Services for Title V Operating Permit Compliance for Lyons VA (New Jersey)
Received Date:  01/24/2020
Close Date:  Not Stated
Delivery Point:  113 HOLLAND AVE ALBANY NY 12208
Download documents online
Bid Documents
Request Future Documents
Specifications:
Statement of Work (SOW) CONTRACT TITLE: Environmental Consulting Services for Title V Operating Permit Compliance. BACKGROUND: The VA New Jersey HealthCare System (VANJHCS) Lyons Campus requires an annual service contract with 4 option years to provide compliance assistance with certain Submittal/Action Requirements of our Title V permit. The Title V permit falls under the Air Quality Permitting program of the State of New Jersey, Department of Environmental Protection (NJDEP) ID: 36080, BOP100001) which is responsible for permitting and testing stationary sources of air pollution to ensure they do not affect air quality. The sources under permit at the VANJHCS Lyons campus are the Emergency Diesel Generators, Waste Oil Heater and the Central Heating Plant Boilers. The Title V permit lists a number of applicable requirements which the VANJHCS Lyons must comply with. The several specific requirements are listed below as various tasks. SCOPE OF WORK: The contractor will furnish all labor, materials, supplies, equipment and fees necessary to accomplish the services required in this scope of work specifically Tasks 1 thru 4 as outlined below. The contractor shall be an engineer/scientist who is knowledgeable with the Clean Air Act and specifically with the Title V permit of VANJHCS Lyons. Specific requirements are listed below. The Contractor shall also provide the deliverables listed below in accordance with the schedule provided under the deliverables section of this SOW. Task 1 a) submit the online semi-annual deviation report, b) submit the online annual compliance certification, and c) sulfur reports from fuel oil usage to NJDEP. 1. Deviation (Semi-Annual) Reports (as per the permit, subject item FC, Ref#13). There are two Deviation Reports that need to be submitted annually. The contractor will review all the requirements of the Title V permit and prepare the online semi-annual compliance reports. The records and logbooks maintained by VANJHCS Lyons will be reviewed while making this determination. The contractor will submit the draft reports to VANJHCS Lyons for review. The comments will be incorporated into the final submittals due by January 30th, 2020, and July 30th, 2020. 2. Annual Compliance Certification (as per the permit, subject item FC, Ref#7). Per NJDEP, the semi-annual and annual report may be combined for compliance submittal. The contractor will review all the requirements of the Title V permit. The contractor will prepare the online joint annual and semi-annual compliance report based on the information provided The contractor will submit the draft compliance certification to the VANJHCS Lyons for review. The comments if any shall be incorporated into the final and this annual certification is due to NJDEP by January 30th, 2020. 3. Sulfur Reports (as per the permit, U17, U18, & U19 OS Summary, Ref#27 and U20 & U21, OS Summary, Ref#26). Fuel Supplier Certifications are to be submitted semi-annually in the required format as specified in the permit. The contractor shall coordinate with the fuel supplier to establish the format required for each certification. VANJHCS Lyons will provide the contractor a copy of the Bill of Lading etc. Task 2 a) submit the online annual combustion adjustment requirements reports to NJDEP, and b) submittal of fuel oil #2 exemption certification to NJDEP. 1. Annual Combustion Adjustment Reports to NJDEP for RY2019 (as per permit, U17, U18, & U19 OS Summary, Ref #6 and U20 & U21, OS Summary, Ref#5). The boilers annual adjustment testing has to be submitted to NJDEP. It is to be noted that the contractor will not conduct the annual tune up, which will be done by VANJHCS/other contractors. VANJHCS will provide the reports to the contractor who will only ensure that the report covers the testing requirements of NJDEP and submit the same. 2. Annual Fuel Oil #2 Exemption for CY2019 (as per permit, U17, U18 & U19, OS2, Ref#11 and U20 & U21, OS2, Ref#11). A certification of exemption shall be submitted to NJDEP by March 1st of every year to ensure the use of fuel oil #2 on the boilers was due to emergencies and or maintenance/ testing purposes. VANJHCS will provide the contractor with the data needed to complete the certification letter to NJDEP Regional Enforcement Office. The contractor will provide a draft to VANJHCS for review, and final certification. Task 3 a) Task 3 includes the air emission statement that is required to be submitted by May 15th of every year. 1. Emission Statement (as per the permit, subject item FC, Ref#6). The annual emission statement for CY 2019 should be submitted to NJDEP before May 15th, 2020. The contractor will calculate the emissions and submit it in RADIUS. VANJHCS will provide the contractor with the necessary data and logbooks to calculate the emissions. Task 4 a) Task 4 includes compliance support to provide assistance with NJDEP information request and correspondence in regard to the Title V. 1. Title V Operating Permit (BOP100001). The Title V permit has applicable requirements for the various sources in the permit. NJDEP enforcement and permitting divisions frequently request additional information in relation to the permit. The contractor will provide the support to assist with information and document submittal requested by the agency. DELIVERABLES Task 1 a) Task 1 Deliverables include: 1. Semi-Annual Deviation Report The contractor shall prepare and submit electronic and hard copy version of Semi-Annual Deviation Reports (draft and final). The Semi-Annual Deviation Reports are due to Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and NJDEP by January 30th, 2020, and July 30th 2020. Per NJDEP, the semi-annual and annual report may be combined for compliance submittal. 2. Annual Compliance Certification. . Per NJDEP, the semi-annual and annual report may be combined for compliance submittal. The annual compliance certification will be combined with the semi-annual report for submittal to EPA and NJDEP by January 30th, 2020. 3. Sulfur Reports The contractor shall submit the semi Annual Sulfur Reports. The first Semi Annual Sulfur Report is due to EPA and NJDEP by January 30th, 2020. The second report is due by July 30th, 2020. Task 2 b) Task 2 Deliverables include: 1. Annual Boiler Tune-up Reports. The annual boiler reports for Q4 CY2019, will be submitted to NJDEP. It is to be noted that the contractor will not conduct the annual tune up, which will be done by VANJHCS/other contractors. VANJHCS will provide the reports and the contractor will only ensure that the report covers the testing requirements of NJDEP and submit the same. 2. Annual Fuel Oil #2 Exemption. The contractor will prepare a certification letter on behalf of VAMC to be submitted to NJDEP Regional Enforcement Office. The letter will provide information on reason for using Fuel oil #2 on Boilers #1, #2, #3, #4 & #5. The letter will be submitted to NJDEP by March 1st, 2020. Task 3 c) Task 3 Deliverables include: 1. Annual Emission Statement. The contractor shall prepare and submit electronic and hard copy version of the annual emission statement in RADIUS to NJDEP by May 15th, 2020. Task 4 d) Task 4 Deliverable include: 1. Support Documentation VANJHCS Lyons will be provided with copies of documentation that is submitted to NJDEP in response to any requests related to Title V Operating Permit requirements. PERIOD OF PERFORMANCE: This is an annual service contract for a period of one (1) year with four (4) option year renewals. All work done by the contractor, including submission of all required data shall be completed by December 31, 2020 for the base year. The tasks contain the specific dates for all due dates of permit requirements. PLACE OF PERFORMANCE: All work will be done at a location determined by the contractor. OTHER RELATED SERVICES (NOT INCLUDED IN THE SCOPE OF WORK): Any services not expressly stated in this statement of work are not authorized. Any additional services performed that are not authorized by the contracting officer will be considered inclusive. Qualifications/Certifications It is expected that the contractor is an engineer/scientist who is knowledgeable with the Clean Air Act and specifically with the Title V permit of VANJHCS Lyons. occurs in this certification the contractor will provide the lab certification necessary to remain compliant. Ultraviolet Systems maintenance. PERIOD OF PERFORMANCE: This is an annual service contract for a period of one (1) year with four (4) option year renewals. Title:  R799--Strategic Capital Investment Planning (SCIP) IDIQ
Received Date:  01/24/2020
Close Date:  Not Stated
Delivery Point:  TBD

Bid Documents
Request Future Documents
Specifications:
2 1 Description The Program Contracting Office Central (PCAC) plans on submitting a solicitation in the next 30 days for the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA), Office of Asset Enterprise Management (OAEM) for the purpose of selecting a contractor to provide for updating the Strategic Capital Investment Planning (SCIP) Long-Range Action Plan summaries using revised data; creating new and updating current SCIP training materials, including SCIP Automation Tool (SAT) guidance documents; providing support for reviewing and validating the SCIP Action Plans; completing summary reports of the Action Plan final submissions; providing support for the validation of Business Cases; providing Help Desk staff to assist SCIP Users in the preparation of Action Plan projects and Business Case applications; facilitating the prioritization of the SCIP Decision Criteria; providing SCIP program management support; updating the current cost-effectiveness analysis template; conducting selected Capital Program Management Requirements Program (CPRMP) reviews and final documents; providing oversight support for execution of SCIP approved construction projects from 2012 through 2020 SCIP processes; providing support for the preparation of, and during select SCIP meetings via note taking, and providing a summary report of the meeting findings. This will be a combined synopsis/solicitation Indefinite Delivery/Indefinite Quantity (IDIQ) contract for commercial items prepared in accordance with the format in Federal Acquisition Regulation (FAR) subpart 12.6, Streamlined Procedures for Evaluation and Solicitation for Commercial Items, as supplemented with additional information included in this notice. This solicitation will be a request for proposals (RFP). The associated North American Industrial Classification System (NAICS) code for this procurement is 541611, with a small business size standard of $15 million. This will be a 100% set-aside for Service Disabled Veteran Owned Small Business (SDVOSB). Background: The Department of Veterans Affairs (VA), Office of Asset Enterprise Management (OAEM), is held accountable for meeting a number of requirements pertaining to its capital asset management. Capital asset initiatives, which include the enhanced-use lease (EUL) program and the Strategic Capital Investment Planning (SCIP) process, are coordinated to ensure capital investments are based on sound business practices and principles and, most importantly, meet Veterans health care, benefits and burial needs. Performance Period: This IDIQ shall be in effect for five years. The work on each task order placed under this IDIQ is anticipated to begin within thirty calendar days of award of the task order. However, each individual task order shall state the specific performance period. Type of Contract: This is anticipated to be a single award IDIQ contract. Firm Fixed price task orders will be generated with a detailed PWS and issued by a Contracting Officer. The maximum (ceiling) amount is estimated at $7,000,000.00 over a five-year performance period. The contract has a onetime minimum of $2,500.00. The contractor must demonstrate it possesses both general and specialized capability, knowledge, and skills. Place of Performance: The primary place of performance will be at the contractor s facilities; however, some task orders may require work to be performed at a Government facility (in such case, the place of performance will be specific in the PWS of the task order). Any work at the Government site shall not take place outside of normal business hours, which are generally between 7:30 am and 4:30 pm, or on Federal holidays or weekends unless directed by the Contracting Officer (CO). IDIQ Title: Strategic Capital Investment Planning (SCIP) Indefinite Delivery/Indefinite Quantity (IDIQ). The initial Task Order for this IDIQ will be solicited for simultaneously with the IDIQ solicitation. The magnitude of this first Task Order will be between $500,000 and $1,000,000. No questions concerning this solicitation will be answered at this time, as there will be an opportunity to submit questions after the solicitation has been posted. If you would like to send an email expressing interest in this project, that will be greatly appreciated. Point of Contact Emails expressing interest in this project should be sent to the Contract Specialist, Steve Mock at steven.mock@va.gov.

Title:  R799--Database Support
Received Date:  01/24/2020
Close Date:  02/14/2020

Description This is a combined synopsis/solicitation for commercial items prepared in accordance with the format in Federal Acquisition Regulation (FAR) subpart 12.6, Streamlined Procedures for Evaluation and Solicitation for Commercial Items, as supplemented with additional information included in this notice. This announcement constitutes the only solicitation; quotations are being requested, and a separate written solicitation document will not be issued. This is a new procurement with no incumbent. This solicitation is a request for quotation (RFQ). The solicitation document and incorporated provisions and clauses are those in effect through Federal Acquisition Circular [FAC 2005-95, effective 19 Jan 2017]. The associated North American Industrial Classification System (NAICS) code for this procurement is 541611, with a small business size standard of $15 million. OAEM s Energy Management Program Service (EMPS) collects, tracks and analyzes energy project information for both direct funded projects and financed performance contracts. Over the years, the system for maintaining and reporting project information has been improved and modified. It now contains current and historical information on EMPS projects through the contracting and construction processes, as well as completion/acceptance information where applicable. The EMPS team seeks support to implement further improvements to the system, to include both planned minor improvements and resolution of issues as they arise. The Contractor shall provide support for EMPS use of the project tracking system by troubleshooting and correcting issues as they arise and making minor improvements to the system and the reports it generates. The Contractor shall also train selected VA staff on relevant aspects of the system so that they are able to troubleshoot and address minor issues in the future. Please see Attachment 1 Performance Work Statement for project details. Evaluation of Offers Award shall be made to the offeror whose quote offers the best value to the government, considering technical capability, past performance, and price. The government will evaluate information based on the procedures authorized in FAR Part 13.106-2 Evaluation of Quotations of Offers using the following evaluation criteria: 1) Technical Evaluation The evaluation process will consider whether the proposal demonstrates a clear understanding of the technical features involved in meeting the requirements of the solicitation. 2) Price The contractor s quote shall include their proposed labor categories, rates and number of hours by task, together with associated delivery dates and sub milestone dates (if any). The Government will evaluate offers by adding all line item prices - the Total of All CLINS will be that sum. 3) Past Performance The Vendor s quote must include a summary description of at least three but no more than five prior contracts/orders per team member/sub-contractor for projects completed within the last five years with organizations with similar mission and functional domains, and of comparable size, complexity and scope. These references must also include: Contract/Order Number, brief description of the project, type of contract, amount of the contract Contracting Officer s Name and Phone Number, Government agency Contracting Officer s Representative Name and Phone Number The contractor must indicate whether they were the prime contractor, sub-contractor or other teaming arrangement. Prime shall indicate which aspect they are directly responsible for of this requirement. The Offeror is required to provide references for the above projects. In the event the company itself does not have relevant past performance, references may be submitted on contracts performed by the Key Personnel of the company. The VA reserves the right to contact all the references that the Offeror lists. Evaluation Approach A. All quotes shall be subject to evaluation by Government personnel. The Government intends to award without discussions based upon the initial evaluation of quotes. However, it may be determined necessary to conduct discussions if award cannot be made on the initial quotes submitted. B. All Offerors are advised that, in the interest of efficiency, the Government reserves the right to conduct the evaluation in the most effective manner. The Government reserves the right to evaluate all Offerors technical quotes should it desire to conduct discussions, or otherwise determine it to be in the Government s best interest. C. The quote will be evaluated strictly in accordance with its written content. Quotes which merely restate the requirement or state that the requirement will be met, without providing supporting rationale, are not sufficient. Offerors who fail to meet the minimum requirements of the solicitation will be rated Unacceptable and thus, ineligible for award. D. Unbalanced Pricing - The Government may evaluate whether the Offeror has submitted unbalanced pricing. An unbalanced price is one where the price of one or more contract line items is significantly overstated or understated and which will result in the Government paying an unreasonably high price for contract performance or otherwise present an unacceptable level of risk to the Government. If the Contracting Officer determines that the risk is unacceptable, then the bid or offer can be rejected. Specifications:
The Naval Supply Systems Command (NAVSUP) Fleet Logistics Center (FLC) Norfolk Contracting Department, Norfolk, VA 23511-3392, intends to award a single, indefinite-delivery, indefinite-quantity-type contract with firm-fixed-price provisions for test and evaluation services in support of Commander Operational Test and Evaluation Force (COMPTEVFOR) Division 40, Undersea Warfare. The Government will solicit and award using the policies and procedures of FAR Part 12, Acquisition of Commercial Items; FAR Part 15, Contracting by Negotiation; FAR Subpart 16.5, Indefinite-Delivery Contracts; and FAR Subpart 19.14, Service-Disabled Veteran-Owned Small Business Procurement Program. Services will commence on/around 16 November 2020 and continue through 15 November 2025 for the five-year basic ordering period. The contract will contain the option to extend services in accordance with FAR clause 52.217-8 to allow for performance through 15 May 2026 if exercised. A request for information (RFI)/sources sought notice (number N00189COTFRFI) associated with this solicitation was posted on 28 June 2019 to identify interested sources and to obtain feedback on a draft Performance Work Statement. As a result of information obtained from responses to the RFI/sources sought notice, this requirement will be solicited competitively as a service-disabled, veteran-owned small business set-aside. The activity’s small business office concurs with this determination. The NAICS code applicable to this procurement is 541330. The size standard is $41.5 million. The Product Service Code is R425. The anticipated award date is no later than 15 September 2020. This requirement is in support of the Undersea Warfare (USW) Division (Code 40), which tests and evaluates all undersea warfare systems, including submarine, surface, aviation, and unmanned underwater vehicle (UUV) anti-submarine warfare and mine warfare systems under the most operationally realistic conditions possible. The division’s main effort is to assist in the acquisition process, conduct tests, and provide timely and accurate evaluations to characterize system performance and resulting capability. COMOPTEVFOR requires contractor technical and analytical support services in the definition, conduct, and analysis of structured Operational Test and Evaluation of United States Navy USW systems. These support services are required in one or more of the following forms: o Test Design o Test Planning o Modeling and Simulation Support o Test Execution o Post-Test Iterative Process and Reporting o Cyber Survivability Test Planning o Administrative Support o Financial Tracking and Support The primary place of performance is Norfolk, VA. However, performance may also be required in numerous locations within and outside the continental United States. The solicitation, any documents related to this procurement, and all amendments issued will be in electronic form. THE SOLICITATION IS NOT YET AVAILABLE. The expected availability date is in January 2020. Once available, the solicitation will be posted to this site (Navy Electronic Commerce Online or NECO, https://www.neco.navy.mil.). The NECO website has a “submit bid” button next to the solicitation number. DO NOT use the “submit bid” button on NECO to submit a proposal. All responsible sources may submit a proposal that will be considered by the Government. By submitting a proposal, the offeror will be self-certifying that neither the principal corporate officials nor owners are currently suspended, debarred, or otherwise ineligible to receive contracts from any federal agency. Failure to do so may represent grounds for refusing to accept the proposal. By submission of a proposal, the offeror acknowledges the requirement that a prospective awardee must be registered in the System for Award Management (SAM) database prior to award, during performance, and through final payment of any contract resulting from the solicitation, except for awards to foreign vendors for work to be performed outside the United States. Lack of registration in the SAM database will make an offeror ineligible for award. Offerors may obtain information on registration and annual confirmation requirements by calling 1-866-606-8220, or via the Internet at https://www.sam.gov.
